title:
In fairness to former S.C. Justice Reyes, his recent public remarks captured headlines with his appeal. But the prevailing sentiment among the public goes beyond appeals to moral responsibility. What the majority of the people urgently seek is justice--the immediate investigation of those responsible and the recovery of all public funds unlawfully appropriated.

This demand for accountability has become even more pronounced following the under oath testimony of the Discaya spouses that they became billionaires onward during the Duterte administration. These are not anonymous allegations. They are admissions against penal interest, made in a formal oversight hearing, punishable by perjury.
The testimony points to systematic corruption, not a one-off incident.

Prima facie evidence exists of violations of: RA 3019, Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act and Plunder (RA 7080), if amount exceeds P50 million. The government need not prove intent to accumulate wealth--the accumulation itself proves intent. And self-incriminating testimony triggers immediate investigatory jurisdiction.

title:
Under Article XI of the 1987 Philippine Constitution and Section 13 of Republic Act 6770 (The Ombudsman Act), the Office of the Ombudsman has the exclusive authority to investigate and prosecute public officials for graft, corruption and plunder.

Once the evidence is transmitted, the Ombudsman is legally obligated to evaluate evidence. If sufficient basis exists, a formal criminal investigation must commence and may direct: asset preservation or freezing accounts, subpoena records and filing of charges before the Sandiganbayan.

The Ombudsman does not need permission from any branch or agency of government. Neither political nor executive preference can bar prosecution.
(Ombudsman v. Court of Appeals, G.R. 164990)
